WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.200
[Amit Varma]: Before we move on with this episode of the Scene in the Unseen, do check out another

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: awesome podcast from IVM Podcast, Cyrus Says, hosted by my old buddy, Cyrus Brochia.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:23.200
[Amit Varma]: When it comes to economics, one of my complaints is that people think in zero sum ways. They

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.920
[Amit Varma]: assume that if someone wins something, someone else must lose. The rich can get rich only

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:32.280
[Amit Varma]: if the poor get poorer, and industrialists can only make money if poor workers down the

00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:37.200
[Amit Varma]: line get exploited. This is why they feel, as Jawaharlal Nehru once said, that profit

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:41.600
[Amit Varma]: is a dirty word. The only solution to poverty, they think, is to redistribute from the poor

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:46.560
[Amit Varma]: to the rich. But the thing is, economies grow and societies prosper because the world works

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:51.760
[Amit Varma]: in a positive some way. Every voluntary transaction makes both parties better off. The writer

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:56.360
[Amit Varma]: John Stossel once called this the double thank you moment. When you buy a cup of coffee at

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:00.720
[Amit Varma]: a cafe, the guy at the counter says thank you when you hand over your money, and you

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:05.440
[Amit Varma]: say thank you when you receive the coffee. Both of you benefited, neither of you exploited

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:06.440
[Amit Varma]: the other.

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:10.320
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me that there is another field besides economics in which zero sum thinking

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:15.520
[Amit Varma]: is a mistake, and that is geopolitics. Except that in geopolitics there are both positive

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:21.360
[Amit Varma]: sum games and negative sum games. A negative sum game is one in which both parties lose.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And a particularly bad kind of negative sum game is one in which both parties get trapped

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:32.440
[Amit Varma]: in a spiral where every action makes both parties worse off, but each is forced to stay

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:34.720
[Amit Varma]: in the game. There is no way out.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Is the conflict between India and Pakistan like this? It's clear to me that there's

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.160
[Amit Varma]: no easy way out of this conflict. It's also clear to me that most ways out will make the

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:48.720
[Amit Varma]: situation worse, not better, for both parties. But doing nothing is also not an option. How

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: did we get here? What can we do to get out of here? Is there anything we can do to get

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.720
[Amit Varma]: out of here?

