00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Srinath, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Good to be here. We are recording this on

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.360
[Amit Varma]: March 8, which is a Friday and this episode releases on March 11, which is a Monday. So

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:52.880
[Amit Varma]: if anything happens on the weekend, we are not to blame for it. So Srinath, what do you

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:57.640
[Guest]: make of the situation right now? Well, at this point of time, it does seem

00:03:57.640 --> 00:04:04.160
[Guest]: like the situation has calmed down. The immediate crisis at hand because of the fallout of the

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:09.480
[Guest]: Pulwama attacks, at least the military dimension of it in terms of active operations, etc.

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:15.040
[Guest]: has been curtailed. The Indian government has stated quite explicitly that, you know,

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:19.680
[Guest]: operations are sort of at an end and that diplomatic action will continue. But this

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:26.200
[Guest]: is very much an evolving situation in a sense that the next crisis is only as far away as

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:30.960
[Guest]: the next terrorist attack is. And I say this with more than a hint of trepidation in my

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:35.720
[Guest]: voice, because the next time around, I think it can be a lot more dangerous as a result

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:39.840
[Amit Varma]: of what has happened this time around. In case any listener is binging on the show

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:44.400
[Amit Varma]: in the year 2023 and just wants a little perspective on what's happened so far, there was an attack

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:51.920
[Amit Varma]: in Pulwama, where around 40 people died. And after that, India responded with a surgical

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:57.520
[Amit Varma]: airstrike, the results of which are debated, but there definitely was a surgical airstrike.

00:04:57.520 --> 00:05:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And after which there was an air skirmish the next day where India claimed that we had

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.440
[Amit Varma]: downed an F-16, but there's no evidence of that yet at the time of speaking. And they

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:13.440
[Amit Varma]: captured one of our pilots who was then released. And that kind of seemed to give both sides

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:17.880
[Amit Varma]: a way out of the situation where Pakistan could say, look, we want peace and we're releasing

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:22.240
[Amit Varma]: the guy and India could say that, look, they gave the guy back because we are so strong

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:25.360
[Amit Varma]: and we've done the surgical strike and we don't need to do any more. Is that how you

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:26.360
[Amit Varma]: look at it?

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:32.600
[Guest]: Well, yes, I think at this point of time, both sides have enough to claim victory. And

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:36.960
[Guest]: in as much as that allows them to sort of back off from a further spiral of escalation

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:42.200
[Guest]: and another round of military action. I think that's a good thing. And of course, a lot

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:48.120
[Guest]: depends on how domestic audiences in both countries will receive the sort of, you know,

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:53.180
[Guest]: established narratives of what has happened in this context. And in as much as diplomatic

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:58.320
[Guest]: action is now going to be foregrounded and there are going to be things like listing

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:04.680
[Guest]: of Masood Azhar in the sort of United Nations list of terrorists and so on. There will be

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:09.760
[Guest]: other kinds of diplomatic pressure that will be built up on Pakistan, the financial action

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:16.840
[Guest]: task force and other avenues. So the sort of India's struggle against terrorism continues.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:21.160
[Guest]: But I think it's safe to say that for the time being, the military dimension of it takes

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:26.600
[Guest]: a bit of a backseat, but it remains latent. I mean, and that provides the background context

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:30.840
[Guest]: against which many further diplomatic and other options will be exercised.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:35.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, I want to come back to the current situation at the end of this episode, because what I

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:39.960
[Amit Varma]: was hoping our conversation would do and which is why I invited you is, I wanted to get a

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:46.520
[Amit Varma]: better sense of the history of the conflict and also kind of sharpen the lens through

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:51.800
[Amit Varma]: which to view it. What are the strategic imperatives? What are the political imperatives? What,

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:55.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, how does one really view it? What are the options open to both parties and so

00:06:55.520 --> 00:07:01.560
[Amit Varma]: on? Where do we start? I mean, obviously, we can just go a long way back to forever.

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:08.920
[Amit Varma]: But if we talk about specifically cross-border terrorism supported by Pakistan, you know,

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:11.560
[Amit Varma]: where should we start when we think about it?

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:16.360
[Guest]: I think a good starting point would be the late 1980s. Because that's the time when obviously

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:22.200
[Guest]: the insurgency in Kashmir really kicks off. And that insurgency then gives Pakistan and

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:28.200
[Guest]: its inter-services intelligence an opportunity to really find another way of inflicting further

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:34.320
[Guest]: pain on India, challenge its control and hold over Jammu and Kashmir. But we should remember

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:39.440
[Guest]: that 1980s was also an important point of time in the sort of nuclear history of the

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:45.520
[Guest]: subcontinent. That is the time at which the Indian government more or less came to some

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:50.400
[Guest]: firm conclusions that the Pakistani nuclear program, which was a covert one, had actually

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:55.600
[Guest]: sort of developed considerably by that point of time. Again, it's worth recalling that,

00:07:55.600 --> 00:08:01.960
[Guest]: you know, in the early 1980s, when Pakistan was very actively supporting the sort of,

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:05.840
[Guest]: you know, operations against the Red Army in Afghanistan by through the Mujahideen and

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:11.380
[Guest]: so on. That was also the period when the United States, the Reagan administration turned a

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:16.680
[Guest]: blind eye to many bits and pieces of evidence that were emerging about Pakistan's pursuit

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:22.040
[Guest]: of a covert nuclear program. In fact, we have evidence about how the Reagan administration

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:28.160
[Guest]: willingly turned a blind eye to many very strong irrefutable pieces of evidence that

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:32.960
[Guest]: Pakistan was actually pursuing a covert nuclear option and that it was being supported by

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:38.600
[Guest]: China in different ways, perhaps to the extent of carrying out a test for Pakistan on a Chinese

00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:43.760
[Guest]: site. So by the late 1980s, the Indians are pretty sure that the Pakistani nuclear program

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:49.120
[Guest]: is pretty well advanced. It is in that context that India also decides then to start thinking

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:53.480
[Guest]: about weaponization of its own program. We had demonstrated capability as far back as

00:08:53.480 --> 00:08:59.240
[Guest]: 1974, but had desisted from any move towards weaponization in the next, you know, decade

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:04.880
[Guest]: and a half and that begins to change. So the late 1980s, therefore, seems to me to be the

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:11.280
[Guest]: right starting point because that's the time when this kind of combination of insurgency

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:17.760
[Guest]: and terrorism as a tool being used by Pakistan, along with unrest in Kashmir and Pakistan's

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:23.920
[Guest]: possession of some kind of, you know, strong nuclear capability actually comes together.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:28.880
[Guest]: And it is the fusion of these that allows Pakistan to continue to build up its support

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:33.720
[Guest]: for insurgency because now it believes that it has a nuclear shield, which will deter

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:38.740
[Guest]: India from carrying out any major conventional operations. I mean, just to give you an example,

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:43.060
[Guest]: if you go back to the 1965 war, that was a war which also began because of Pakistani

00:09:43.060 --> 00:09:48.840
[Guest]: support for insurgents or attempt to infiltrate people into Kashmir and so on. But what was

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:53.040
[Guest]: the Indian response? It was very quickly to strike across the line of control. When the

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:58.200
[Guest]: Pakistanis responded by carrying out a conventional military attack on Akhnur, India responded

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:03.280
[Guest]: by opening up the Punjab front, right? So you could escalate and demonstrate your conventional

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:08.400
[Guest]: superiority because you are the more powerful country in a conventional sense. But once

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:12.960
[Guest]: the Pakistanis possessed some kind of nuclear capability, even if it was shadowy, even if

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:18.920
[Guest]: it was not demonstrated, but more importantly, once India knew that Pakistan had that capability

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:24.200
[Guest]: and Pakistan knew that India knew, then the Pakistani strategy is to say that India's

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:29.120
[Guest]: conventional superiority is now going to be negated by this nuclear shield that we have

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:33.480
[Guest]: acquired. So that then allows them to believe that they can continue to use subconventional

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:40.120
[Guest]: means like insurgency and terrorism to impose costs on India without having to fear a retaliatory

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:45.000
[Guest]: response by the Indians. And that really is the dilemma with which we are still grappling.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.520
[Guest]: So in that sense, the late 1980s may be a useful starting point.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:53.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's take a step back to a period you're very familiar with. In fact, the Bangladesh

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:57.320
[Amit Varma]: war, which ends in 71 and we recorded an episode about this last week, but it airs two weeks

00:10:57.320 --> 00:11:02.160
[Amit Varma]: later on March 25th. But regardless of that, so it's after 1971 when Pakistan lose and

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:06.520
[Amit Varma]: they're humiliated because, you know, the country is basically torn into two. I mean,

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:11.840
[Amit Varma]: they lose East Pakistan as it were, which is when they make the turn towards nuclear.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:17.840
[Amit Varma]: So you know, my question there is, what does Pakistan want? What are its long term aims

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:21.400
[Amit Varma]: against India? How does it look at South Asia? How does it look at itself?

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:27.120
[Guest]: Well, at one level, Pakistan's long term aim has been to sort of challenge India's control

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:31.000
[Guest]: over Jammu and Kashmir, which it believes as a Muslim majority province should have

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.420
[Guest]: rightly sort of joined Pakistan at the time of partition and independence. And because

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:40.720
[Guest]: it did not, they have, you know, successively at various points of time, attempted to use

00:11:40.720 --> 00:11:46.240
[Guest]: force in order to wrest control of Kashmir from India. You saw that happening in October

00:11:46.240 --> 00:11:52.120
[Guest]: 1947. In fact, even before Kashmir had formally joined India, you saw that happening in 1965.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:56.560
[Guest]: We've, you know, seen that happening through the course of the insurgency, which began

00:11:56.560 --> 00:12:02.280
[Guest]: in the late 1980s. So Pakistan's aims have been consistent. It is a territorially revisionist

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:07.600
[Guest]: power, which wants a piece of territory which is disputed between India and Pakistan to

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:09.080
[Amit Varma]: be entirely under its control.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:12.600
[Amit Varma]: But is it also the case that, I mean, the military is dominant then, is it also the

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:16.920
[Amit Varma]: case that the incentives of the army are such that they want to keep Kashmir on the boil

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:20.720
[Amit Varma]: and they want to keep this conflict going. So that is where they get their power from.

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And it could therefore be said that their actions and their focus on Kashmir is a consequence

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:30.200
[Amit Varma]: of this. And they don't necessarily care about Kashmir per se, like in the same way that

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:34.600
[Amit Varma]: within India, for example, a lot of people who make noises about cow slaughter don't

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:41.880
[Amit Varma]: really care about cows. It's a proxy for the bigotry. So in that sense, is Kashmir a proxy

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:47.880
[Amit Varma]: for the military's need to keep the conflict bubbling over?

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:53.060
[Guest]: Well, yes, in the sense that you could make an argument that Kashmir comes very handy

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:58.280
[Guest]: to the Pakistan army to sort of talk about this, you know, threat from India to the existence

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:02.800
[Guest]: of Pakistan and the need to recuperate Pakistan's sort of national territory, which they believe

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:08.720
[Guest]: encompasses Kashmir, at least the Kashmir Valley and so on. And that then gives the

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:13.100
[Guest]: Pakistan army a stronger handle with which to fight out various kinds of institutional

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:18.480
[Guest]: battles and cement its own position within the Pakistani state and society at large.

00:13:18.480 --> 00:13:22.760
[Guest]: But at the same time, it's worth remembering that the Kashmir dispute in some ways predates

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:28.080
[Guest]: the rise to prominence of the, so historically, it's not accurate to say that this was a dispute

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:33.000
[Guest]: which was invented by the Pakistan army. In fact, the decision to send the first round

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:38.640
[Guest]: of irregulars in October 1947, was taken at the time when Jinnah was the governor general.

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:43.600
[Guest]: And he knew quite well, and this is well established in historical records, that he knew that this

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:47.320
[Guest]: operation was being prepared and that the Pakistani state was supporting it. So in a

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:53.400
[Guest]: sense, there is a longer term sort of question about Pakistan's, you know, sense of nationalism,

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:57.640
[Guest]: its rivalry with India, which is crystallized in the Kashmir conflict. And the Pakistan

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:02.800
[Guest]: army, of course, sees Kashmir as a raison d'etre for its own existence, and which allows

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:05.800
[Guest]: it to continually accrue power within their system.

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:10.280
[Amit Varma]: So it kind of works both ways. So coming on to the 80s, so what's really happened is that

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:16.800
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan makes a determined move to become a nuclear power post 71. And India also sort

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:23.480
[Amit Varma]: of flirts with it. And already there is sort of a dynamic developing where Pakistan looks

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:29.400
[Amit Varma]: at the nuclear option as a military necessity, where India seems to look at the nuclear option

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:34.240
[Amit Varma]: more as a strategic necessity, you know, for deterrence and so on, and isn't actually thinking

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:36.520
[Amit Varma]: of using it on the battlefield. Is that correct?

00:14:36.520 --> 00:14:41.120
[Guest]: Well, yes, which is why, you know, from the time that Indians do the first nuclear test

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:46.640
[Guest]: 1974, which incidentally is built, you know, it is euphemistically called a peaceful nuclear

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:50.640
[Guest]: explosion. Now, let's remember that there was a category of nuclear explosions, which

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:55.040
[Guest]: were called PNEs back in the day, and India invoked that category. So it's not like we

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:59.080
[Guest]: sort of conjured it up out of thin air. It was an available sort of way of describing

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:04.680
[Guest]: these activities. And we chose to do that. But what is also interesting, and this is

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:08.720
[Guest]: now reasonably well established in the sort of work which has been done on the nuclear

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:14.680
[Guest]: history of India, is that India did not really think actively of weaponization of the nuclear

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:20.720
[Guest]: thing. Because I think, as you're suggesting, the assumption always was that, you know,

00:15:20.720 --> 00:15:26.160
[Guest]: we needed nuclear weapons or the kind of capability to sort of acquire nuclear weapons, primarily

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:32.600
[Guest]: as a way of demonstrating our political sort of resolve against any attempts at coercion

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:36.840
[Guest]: in the nuclear domain. So right, so you had important adversaries like China, which had

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:42.280
[Guest]: acquired nuclear weapons, you knew that Pakistan was acquiring, in the 1971 context, you had

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:46.600
[Guest]: the United States sending in the Seventh Fleet, which had nuclear weapons on board, to the

00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:52.560
[Guest]: Bay of Bengal, and so on. So in a sense, nuclear weapons and demonstrating that capability

00:15:52.560 --> 00:15:57.960
[Guest]: was seen basically as a way of telling others that India would not back down in the face

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:03.280
[Guest]: of any kind of overt or covert threat of nuclear coercion, right. So it's that really. So in

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:08.600
[Guest]: that sense, it is more at a strategic political level that India was thinking about it. Whereas

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:13.640
[Guest]: for Pakistan, you know, the capability, and then even the moment at which they chose to

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:18.680
[Guest]: sort of start developing that capability, really reflected their lopsided conventional

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:24.240
[Guest]: military balance with India, right. The Bangladesh war really brings it to the fore. Not only

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:29.080
[Guest]: do you lose half of the country, and in some ways, the more populous half, but you have

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:35.240
[Guest]: 93,000 Pakistani soldiers in Indian custody. It is a very starkly humiliating sort of moment,

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:40.960
[Guest]: which exposes Pakistan's conventional military inferiority vis-a-vis India. And in that sense,

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:45.920
[Guest]: they always see nuclear weapons as a way of compensating for that conventional imbalance

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:47.680
[Amit Varma]: of power with India.

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And would you say the quality of your nuclear capabilities to some extent, driven by these

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.640
[Amit Varma]: imperatives, like Pakistan's imperative is to actually have nuclear weapons they can

00:16:56.640 --> 00:17:01.360
[Amit Varma]: use in a variety of different situations, tactically on the battlefield or otherwise,

00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:06.320
[Amit Varma]: and so on. While for India, what is important is to have nuclear weapons, so as to be able

00:17:06.320 --> 00:17:10.960
[Amit Varma]: to signal credibly that they are nuclear power. And does that then impact the intensity with

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:14.480
[Amit Varma]: which you pursue building an actual nuclear arsenal?

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:18.640
[Guest]: Well, yes, but even in the case of Pakistan, these are things which happen only over a

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:23.280
[Guest]: period of time, right? Because till such time you have covert capabilities, or you do not

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:28.160
[Guest]: declare yourself and what nuclear weapons state, it becomes difficult to then, you know,

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:33.640
[Guest]: try out a range of other things without others picking up on what your actions are. So in

00:17:33.640 --> 00:17:41.080
[Guest]: that sense, it's only in the post 1998 phase that Pakistan also starts thinking about how

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:46.200
[Guest]: to make these nuclear weapons kind of more integrated with conventional sort of, you

00:17:46.200 --> 00:17:49.640
[Guest]: know, military power, not necessarily in terms of deploying them for, you know, for actual

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:54.080
[Guest]: military use. But how do you use that in ways that will negate India's conventional superiority,

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:55.080
[Guest]: right?

00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:59.640
[Guest]: So that design is there in the mind, but it's only in the post 1998 phase that the Pakistanis

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:05.560
[Guest]: really start seeing it. But what is interesting is that even before Pakistan overtly sort

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:10.920
[Guest]: of does its nuclear tests in 1998, they are already aware of the fact that Indians are

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:18.400
[Guest]: aware of this, and then use that to push in more insurgency, terrorism in the context

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:23.120
[Guest]: of Jammu and Kashmir, but also in other parts of India in that period. Of course, it is

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:28.160
[Guest]: a context in Jammu and Kashmir, which kind of allows them to sort of do it. But the fact

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:33.120
[Guest]: that they are able to leverage that context is in some ways unthinkable without the presence

00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:37.240
[Guest]: of some kind of even covert nuclear capability in that early stage.

00:18:37.240 --> 00:18:42.040
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we go on to discuss nuclear deterrence in detail and how it evolved and

00:18:42.040 --> 00:18:49.200
[Amit Varma]: so on, tell me a little bit about deterrence per se. What are the different kinds of deterrence?

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:57.520
[Guest]: Well, the word deterrence comes from the verb deter, which means to sort of stop someone

00:18:57.520 --> 00:19:04.400
[Guest]: from doing something that someone wants to do, right. So the way we think about deterrence

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:11.760
[Guest]: is typically that you think about it in terms of deterrence by way of threatening prospective

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:16.240
[Guest]: punishment, right. I mean, think about any day to day circumstance, you know, I have

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:21.200
[Guest]: young kids, right. So how do I tell my kids not to do something is by saying, if you do

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:25.040
[Guest]: that, then this is the punishment that you will get, you know, you will be sort of grounded

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:28.680
[Guest]: for a week or something to that effect, right. I mean, in back in the day, parents used to

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:32.280
[Guest]: actually give it to you. I hope they are listening to this. Do they listen to my podcast?

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:35.880
[Guest]: Yeah. So, so, you know, back in the day, when I was growing up, parents had stronger ways

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:40.560
[Guest]: of deterring you by giving you a, you know, a few tight whacks. I suppose we are, you

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:44.320
[Guest]: know, at a level of civilization where those things are at least not to be talked about

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:49.520
[Guest]: on podcasts. So, but that is a standard way of thinking about, right. So you, you, you,

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:54.360
[Guest]: you change someone's behavior or by telling them not to do something by threatening prospective

00:19:54.360 --> 00:20:00.280
[Guest]: punishment. Now, there is another way of thinking about it, which is not just about punishment,

00:20:00.280 --> 00:20:05.080
[Guest]: but which is what you call deterrence by denial, right. Let me give you another example, which

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:10.560
[Guest]: will sort of crystallize this. Now, how do you think about preventing a thief from entering

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:16.800
[Guest]: your house? So one way of doing it is to say that, listen, we have law, which says anyone

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:21.240
[Guest]: who tries to break into someone else's house, if he's caught, will be sort of punished for

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:26.640
[Guest]: so many years, right. So that is a classic case of deterrence by punishment. You have

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:30.280
[Guest]: law on the statute books, you have courts, you have the police, then whole enforcement

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:35.240
[Guest]: machinery precisely to deter people. The idea is not so much to punish someone who's been

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:40.000
[Guest]: caught. The idea is to deter those who may be thinking of such actions in the future.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:44.880
[Guest]: That is what deterrence by punishment is a classic example. But another way of thinking

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:49.000
[Guest]: about the same problem, how to prevent the thief from entering your house, is to say,

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:54.920
[Guest]: I am going to construct a 15 to 20 feet wall all around my house. I'm going to put an electricity

00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:59.200
[Guest]: sort of driven fence all around it. So every thief will know that it's actually next to

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:03.120
[Guest]: impossible to break into this house. That changes his decision calculus about whether

00:21:03.120 --> 00:21:08.440
[Guest]: he should even try it or not. That is called deterrence by denial, right. So another way

00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:13.080
[Guest]: of thinking about this distinction is to say that, you know, all forms of deterrence aim

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:18.920
[Guest]: to influence the cost benefit calculations of whoever is your target, right, whose behavior

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:24.240
[Guest]: you want to change. Now, deterrence by punishment goes after the cost side of the equation because

00:21:24.240 --> 00:21:29.760
[Guest]: you're telling him or her that if you do this, then you're going to incur costs by way of

00:21:29.760 --> 00:21:34.680
[Guest]: my punishment. Yeah. But another way of thinking about it is to say that you go after the benefit

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:39.920
[Guest]: sides of the equation by telling the other person that you won't, in the first instance,

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:44.720
[Guest]: be able to pocket the benefits of whatever it is that you want to do, right. So that

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:49.960
[Guest]: is called deterrence by denial, right. So deterrence works by punishment and by denial.

00:21:49.960 --> 00:21:54.640
[Guest]: These are not mutually exclusive, but there is one salient distinction. Deterrence by

00:21:54.640 --> 00:22:00.240
[Guest]: punishment is typically easier and less costly to execute, whereas deterrence by denial is

00:22:00.240 --> 00:22:04.880
[Guest]: more expensive. Just go back to the example of the thief, right? If I rely on the law

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:09.560
[Guest]: and, you know, the threat of prospective punishment, do I need to do very much? Not. But if I want

00:22:09.560 --> 00:22:14.120
[Guest]: to build a fence and you want to put up walls, I've got to fork out money, right? So deterrence

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:18.200
[Guest]: by denial is the stronger form of deterrence, but it's also the one which is more costly

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:21.800
[Amit Varma]: for you to implement. So in the context of your kids, if you don't want them to watch

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:26.720
[Amit Varma]: too much TV, deterrence by punishment would be to tell them that, listen, you know, no

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:34.400
[Amit Varma]: dinner for you or too tight wax if you watch like TV beyond 9pm. And deterrence by denial

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:38.000
[Amit Varma]: would be not having a television set at home, which is very costly for you because you yourself

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
[Guest]: like television, right?

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.720
[Guest]: And which is my preferred way of deterring them from watching television. I've not had

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:45.920
[Guest]: the privilege of having a television set at home for maybe eight years now.

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:49.960
[Amit Varma]: There you go. And I don't watch news television either. But what does one do about football?

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:56.400
[Amit Varma]: Well, you could argue there is Hotstar. Right. So we'll come back to deterrence by denial

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:01.360
[Amit Varma]: later. But just talking about deterrence by punishment, once Pakistan kind of goes nuclear

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:08.040
[Amit Varma]: and once India goes in that direction as well, through the 80s and up to 98, it's basically

00:23:08.040 --> 00:23:13.160
[Amit Varma]: deterrence by punishment. And it's basically nuclear deterrence where you are either you're

00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:18.280
[Amit Varma]: threatening to go nuclear or anything else you threaten isn't effective because the other

00:23:18.280 --> 00:23:23.240
[Amit Varma]: side can go nuclear and therefore there's not much you can do at all. And you pointed

00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:29.160
[Amit Varma]: me to this excellent paper by Vipin Narang, which is linked on my episode page, which

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:34.840
[Amit Varma]: kind of talks about the different levels of deterrence and especially why Pakistan is

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:39.800
[Amit Varma]: able to deter India, but India is not able to deter Pakistan. And what I learned from

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.760
[Amit Varma]: that was what Narang calls the posture, the nuclear posture of each country of Pakistan

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:51.120
[Amit Varma]: rather changed from 86 to 98. Tell me a little bit more about the different kinds of deterrence

00:23:51.120 --> 00:23:56.760
[Guest]: and how 98 changed the dynamic. Well, I think it's important in the first instance to point

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:02.600
[Guest]: out quite clearly what is it that India wants to deter and what is it that Pakistan wants

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:06.560
[Guest]: to deter. Right. Because those are kind of two different things, even though the issues

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:11.680
[Guest]: and what are the instruments in play are somewhat similar. Right. From the Indian perspective,

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:18.720
[Guest]: the first instance you want to deter the use of any nuclear weapons by a state like Pakistan

00:24:18.720 --> 00:24:25.080
[Guest]: or any other state against India in any context. So there you have a posture of sort of declared

00:24:25.080 --> 00:24:29.120
[Guest]: nuclear policy of massive retaliation. You say that, listen, if you are going to use

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:33.120
[Guest]: force against us, we are going to hit you so hard and punish you so much that it's not

00:24:33.120 --> 00:24:37.160
[Guest]: even going to be worthwhile for you to have initiated this action in the first place.

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:42.760
[Guest]: Right. So, so that is a very clear strategy of deterrence by punishment, but which is

00:24:42.760 --> 00:24:47.680
[Guest]: aimed at the nuclear use. But there is another level at which you want deterrence to operate,

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:52.080
[Guest]: which is to say that you want to deter Pakistan or the terrorist groups which are striking

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:58.160
[Guest]: you from carrying out these terrorist strikes against you. Now, if you want to deter that,

00:24:58.160 --> 00:25:02.800
[Guest]: then frankly, the nuclear deterrence angle does not really come into play because what

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:08.680
[Guest]: you have to have the capability there is in the first instance to either punish Pakistan

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:13.760
[Guest]: and the terrorist organizations which are striking against you, or to be able to create

00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:17.920
[Guest]: systems which will deny them the opportunity to be able to carry out those attacks in the

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:24.120
[Guest]: first place. Right. So there you need either denial or punishment. And, and that's a different

00:25:24.120 --> 00:25:27.520
[Guest]: kind of a level at which you are looking to do deterrence. Now, how does it work from

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:32.000
[Guest]: Pakistani side? Right. From Pakistan's point of view, they know that India, because of

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:36.040
[Guest]: its conventional superiority is unlikely to be using nuclear weapons in the first instance.

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:41.240
[Guest]: So their nuclear weapons really are aimed against deterring India from bringing to bear

00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:45.360
[Guest]: its conventional superiority against Pakistan in any context. Now, that context could be

00:25:45.360 --> 00:25:50.760
[Guest]: that of terrorism, right? So you have a major terrorist attack. India sort of cannot respond

00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:57.160
[Guest]: with a major use of its conventional force, say in the way that it did in 1965, hypothetically,

00:25:57.160 --> 00:26:01.800
[Guest]: because it should then fear that this conflict will escalate to the nuclear level. It could

00:26:01.800 --> 00:26:06.400
[Guest]: invoke, it could sort of push Pakistan to use its nuclear weapons in order to deter

00:26:06.400 --> 00:26:12.480
[Guest]: a conventional use of force by India. Right. So for the Pakistani nuclear weapons, therefore,

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:18.380
[Guest]: are basically a way of negating India's conventional superiority, and then allowing them to continue

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:24.600
[Guest]: to impose costs on India by subconventional means, by which we mean insurgency and terrorism.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:28.280
[Guest]: But putting India in this bind of saying, listen, you have to absorb these costs, but

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:32.720
[Guest]: you cannot punish us in any significant way, because that punishment then carries the risk

00:26:32.720 --> 00:26:37.000
[Guest]: of escalating to a nuclear conflict of some kind. And that is the way in which the Pakistani

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:42.520
[Guest]: strategy of deterrence really operates. Right. And what Narang tries to tell in his paper

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:48.400
[Guest]: is really about how the Pakistani posture has kind of evolved in the period after the

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:53.300
[Guest]: Pakistani sort of nuclear tests of 1998, and also in response to various kinds of actions

00:26:53.300 --> 00:26:57.960
[Guest]: that India has taken. Right. So in that sense, I think the key thing for us to remember is

00:26:57.960 --> 00:27:04.360
[Guest]: that, you know, nuclear deterrence or normal deterrence is like any strategic situation.

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:10.280
[Guest]: Yeah, strategy, the essence of strategy really is interdependent decision making. The decisions

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:14.360
[Guest]: that you want to make depends on the decision that the other side is going to make and vice

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:20.360
[Guest]: versa. Right. So in that sense, it's a constantly evolving iterative game that continues over

00:27:20.360 --> 00:27:25.040
[Guest]: a period of time, which is why game theory provides a very good basic template within

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:28.840
[Amit Varma]: which to think about strategic situations. And are we disadvantaged by the fact that

00:27:28.840 --> 00:27:35.240
[Amit Varma]: because of our rational posturing, and I know first use doctrine and so on, that our actions,

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:40.120
[Amit Varma]: our reactions have so far been relatively predictable, while the Pakistanis have been

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:44.680
[Amit Varma]: relatively unpredictable in the sense we don't really know how they will respond. And therefore,

00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:51.000
[Amit Varma]: whenever we respond to a provocation from them, we tend to play it as safe as we can,

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:54.760
[Amit Varma]: because hey, what if they go nuclear, while in their case, they can do a lot of things

00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:59.200
[Amit Varma]: with impunity, because you know, they know there's a no first news here, they know that,

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:04.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, we are also at some level wary of that kind of escalation, does that matter?

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:08.800
[Guest]: Well, the first thing is to point out the reasons for India's adoption of the no first

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:14.800
[Guest]: use policy, right. So the NFU posture was adopted or announced by the Vajpayee government

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:20.040
[Guest]: soon after the nuclear tests. And the reason that, you know, sort of we kind of adopted

00:28:20.040 --> 00:28:23.400
[Guest]: that posture over a period of time, and then it was kind of, you know, codified in a doctrine

00:28:23.400 --> 00:28:30.440
[Guest]: and so on, was primarily to demonstrate that India is not looking to use nuclear weapons

00:28:30.440 --> 00:28:35.680
[Guest]: in any kind of military, you know, operational context at all, but that we are primarily

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:41.400
[Guest]: looking at it as a device to prevent the use of nuclear weapons as tools of coercion by

00:28:41.400 --> 00:28:45.940
[Guest]: anyone else. So from that perspective, we saw it simply as a deterrent to against the

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:50.600
[Guest]: use of nuclear weapons by any other state. Right now, there has been a lot of criticism

00:28:50.600 --> 00:28:55.200
[Guest]: over the years saying that India is, you know, unnecessarily tying its hands because the

00:28:55.200 --> 00:29:00.720
[Guest]: NFU posture then allows Pakistan to sort of do a range of things without India being able

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:04.960
[Guest]: to invoke its nuclear weapons. But there is a flip side to it. And I think that argument

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:10.160
[Guest]: is kind of worth taking on board, which is to say that if India abandons its no first

00:29:10.160 --> 00:29:14.600
[Guest]: use policy, or let's say it never had a no first use policy, if it had a policy saying,

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:19.200
[Guest]: we reserve the right to use whatever capabilities that we have, depending on our assessment

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:25.160
[Guest]: of what the nature of the threat to India is, then you have to understand that as the

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:31.920
[Guest]: smaller of the two states, Pakistan will be concerned that India may actually use its

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:36.920
[Guest]: nuclear weapons in a first use mode, a first strike, really to take out Pakistani nuclear

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:42.600
[Guest]: capability, because that then neutralizes Pakistan's nuclear capability, and allows

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:46.440
[Guest]: India to bring its conventional superiority to bear. Right. So that is the way if you

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:50.360
[Guest]: are a rational actor, you would imagine that the way India would be thinking about it is

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:53.760
[Guest]: to say that, hey, we have nuclear weapons, let's use these to take out the Pakistani

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:57.880
[Guest]: nukes. Once the Pakistani nukes are gone, we are back to the pre nuclear age, where

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:02.720
[Guest]: it's just the conventional superiority of India, which will kick in. And from Pakistan's

00:30:02.720 --> 00:30:07.480
[Guest]: perspective, that then brings about what, you know, nuclear deterrence or scholars of

00:30:07.480 --> 00:30:14.160
[Guest]: nuclear weapons call a use it or lose it dilemma. So the fear of a first strike could then actually

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:19.720
[Guest]: catalyze them to sort of think about using it very early on in any crisis, rather than

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:24.600
[Guest]: having a restraint, right. So in a sense, India's NFU posture actually allows these

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:28.840
[Guest]: crises not from escalating very quickly. So I think that is a very important part of what

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:33.240
[Guest]: the NFU brings to the table. And I think it's worth remembering that, because at the end

00:30:33.240 --> 00:30:39.040
[Guest]: of the day, the problem that India has been confronting for the last 30 years from Pakistan,

00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:45.520
[Guest]: fundamentally, is at the level of subconventional threats. And whether nuclear first use against

00:30:45.520 --> 00:30:50.160
[Guest]: Pakistan is the proportionate response to that, it's inconceivable that India or any

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:54.400
[Guest]: decision makers sitting in New Delhi will actually assume that nuking Pakistan is the

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:58.280
[Guest]: response to their support for terrorism of whatever scale or magnitude, right.

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:02.280
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, our abandoning the first use doctrine would make first use more likely

00:31:02.280 --> 00:31:05.160
[Guest]: by them. Exactly. I think it will make for much greater

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:10.280
[Guest]: degrees of instability. And it can be a very worrying proposition. We have already seen

00:31:10.280 --> 00:31:14.720
[Guest]: that Pakistan has kind of developed, you know, sort of these tactical nuclear weapons, which

00:31:14.720 --> 00:31:18.280
[Guest]: they have sort of devolved down the chain of command, primarily because they believe

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:22.440
[Guest]: India is trying to develop other forms of, you know, conventional capabilities, which

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:26.440
[Guest]: you can bring to bear very quickly, what used to be called the cold start doctrine, and

00:31:26.440 --> 00:31:31.320
[Guest]: so on, which the Pakistanis believe have to be deterred, right. And in that sense, if

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:35.600
[Guest]: we say that, listen, we are going to bring about a degree of ambiguity in this domain,

00:31:35.600 --> 00:31:40.720
[Guest]: I think that will have consequences of instability. In fact, there is a new paper, which is an

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:45.120
[Guest]: even more interesting paper by Vipin Narang and Chris Clary, which has just come out even

00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:49.920
[Guest]: literally in the last couple of weeks, where they make an interesting argument saying,

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:56.120
[Guest]: why is it that India constantly talks about saying that we need to abandon this NFU? You

00:31:56.120 --> 00:32:00.680
[Guest]: know, is India really moving towards a counterforce kind of strategy, which is saying we are developing

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:05.800
[Guest]: a nuclear strategy, which aims at taking out Pakistani nuclear weapons? Now, if that is

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:12.160
[Guest]: indeed true, then that could introduce very dangerous dynamics very early on in any crisis

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:13.720
[Amit Varma]: between India and Pakistan.

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:19.320
[Amit Varma]: And just to summarise sort of Narang's thesis on how Pakistan's approach changed because

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:24.320
[Amit Varma]: of India going nuclear in 98 was, he talks about three kinds of nuclear postures that

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:29.800
[Amit Varma]: you can have the catalytic, the assured retaliation, and asymmetric escalation. Assured retaliation

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:35.720
[Amit Varma]: is basically what India and China do, which is the no first use doctrine. Catalytic is

00:32:35.720 --> 00:32:41.000
[Amit Varma]: what according to him, Pakistan did between 86 and 98, which is basically, you know, you

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:48.320
[Amit Varma]: are trying to catalyse a third party into intervening. For example, what Israel did

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:52.840
[Amit Varma]: during the Yom Kippur War in 1973 was exactly this, where they showed that they were mobilising

00:32:52.840 --> 00:32:58.760
[Amit Varma]: nuclear weapons so that the US would intervene, and not necessarily to use the weapons per

00:32:58.760 --> 00:33:05.800
[Amit Varma]: se. And in both the brass tacks crisis of 1986, and then the Kashmir crisis of 1990,

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan postured in a catalytic way about its nuclear weaponry so that the US would

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:14.480
[Amit Varma]: intervene at a diplomatic level, which they succeeded in doing. But otherwise, Narang

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:19.720
[Amit Varma]: says India was not actually going to be deterred. And therefore, it wasn't effective. And what

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:25.240
[Amit Varma]: changed with 98 was that because India had gone nuclear to counter that they shifted

00:33:25.240 --> 00:33:31.000
[Amit Varma]: from catalytic to asymmetric escalation, which is basically you are saying that we will use

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.880
[Amit Varma]: it at any point in time, we'll use it on the battlefield, we'll use it as a tactical thing,

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:42.440
[Amit Varma]: we are unpredictable. And the term he used about that strategy was deterrent optimal,

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:47.320
[Amit Varma]: which is that, you know, because Pakistan is doing asymmetric escalation, and you know,

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:51.600
[Amit Varma]: posturing that we will use it at any point in time, and India is saying we won't be the

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:55.800
[Amit Varma]: first to use it, it automatically gives them an advantage over us in the sense that they

00:33:55.800 --> 00:34:00.760
[Amit Varma]: can continue doing subconventional, or, you know, supporting cross border terrorism, basically,

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:07.240
[Amit Varma]: with impunity, knowing that any escalation that we carry out has a threat of nuclear

00:34:07.240 --> 00:34:11.360
[Amit Varma]: escalation. So I think it's in response to this that some people often say that, hey,

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:13.360
[Amit Varma]: we should leave the no first use doctrine.

00:34:13.360 --> 00:34:19.060
[Guest]: Yeah, as I said, I mean, the leaving out the no first use will introduce more dangerous

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:24.000
[Guest]: dynamics in any India Pakistan crisis, in ways that may not necessarily be beneficial

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:29.840
[Guest]: to India, there is no reason for India to adopt a crisis posture, which will somehow

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:33.200
[Guest]: give incentives for the Pakistanis to think that the best thing is for them to use nuclear

00:34:33.200 --> 00:34:38.920
[Guest]: weapons early on, why would we do it? It's suicidal to think that that's in any way a

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:43.480
[Guest]: strategically wise move. So to that extent, I don't think that's there. But there are

00:34:43.480 --> 00:34:47.080
[Guest]: other options that India has been sort of exploring. And in some ways, you know, you

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:51.280
[Guest]: could think about the evolution of Indian strategy towards Pakistan, as primarily a

00:34:51.280 --> 00:34:59.040
[Guest]: search for usable options between the sort of conventional and nuclear realm, in order

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:03.760
[Guest]: to deter Pakistan's subconventional activities, right, which is to say that, listen, the Pakistanis

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:07.920
[Guest]: keep saying that we have these red lines that, you know, we can sort of go asymmetric very

00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:12.320
[Guest]: soon. But actually speaking, if they are a rational actor, they cannot want a nuclear

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:16.640
[Guest]: exchange with India either. Because, you know, India will survive, but Pakistan cannot survive

00:35:16.640 --> 00:35:21.520
[Guest]: a massive retaliation by India, right. That is the premise of India's nuclear deterrent.

00:35:21.520 --> 00:35:25.160
[Guest]: So when the Pakistanis are suggesting that, you know, the nuclear threshold is actually

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:30.560
[Guest]: here, it is not there. And the challenge for Indian strategy, therefore, is to explore

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:35.520
[Guest]: what is the space between conventional and nuclear, where force can be brought to bear

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:42.200
[Guest]: effectively to deter Pakistan's support of subconventional options, right. And so if

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:47.000
[Guest]: you think about, you know, when the 1998 nuclear test happened, India was the first one to

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:54.840
[Guest]: test. Then Indian Home Minister LK Advani said, I believe in Parliament, that, you know,

00:35:54.840 --> 00:36:00.500
[Guest]: now India will start pursuing options like hot pursuit of terrorists across the line

00:36:00.500 --> 00:36:05.640
[Guest]: of control. Because he believed that now that India had gone overtly nuclear, you know,

00:36:05.640 --> 00:36:12.040
[Guest]: it had the sort of ability to, you know, put Pakistan on the mat. But once Pakistanis got

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:17.560
[Guest]: their own nuclear tests in a reciprocal way, then Indian decision makers had to become

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:22.920
[Guest]: a lot more cautious. So, a year down the line, or almost a year down the line, when you had

00:36:22.920 --> 00:36:27.120
[Guest]: the sort of Kargil conflict happening, which was basically an attempt by Pakistanis to

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:32.120
[Guest]: grab territory on the Indian side of the line of control in the Kargil area, the government

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:39.080
[Guest]: of India responded by significant use of force, but ensured that that use of force was contained

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:42.840
[Guest]: to evicting Pakistanis who had come on the Indian side of the line of control. Even the

00:36:42.840 --> 00:36:46.560
[Guest]: use of air power at that point of time was restricted to striking on Pakistanis who were

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:50.840
[Guest]: on the Indian side of the line of control. We did not want to say strike Pakistani logistical

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:55.960
[Guest]: lines or supply lines on the other side. And, you know, in fact, in his memoir on the Kargil

00:36:55.960 --> 00:37:01.660
[Guest]: war, the then Army Chief General VP Malik says that the air chief at that point of time

00:37:01.660 --> 00:37:07.320
[Guest]: pointed out that if we are going to use air power, then it can lead to escalation. And

00:37:07.320 --> 00:37:12.440
[Guest]: the political leadership of the time, which is Prime Minister Vajpayee, took a conscious

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:17.560
[Guest]: decision that India should not cross the line of control, and that operations have to be

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:21.440
[Guest]: carried out on the Pakistanis on this side of the line of control. And again, the reason

00:37:21.440 --> 00:37:26.840
[Guest]: for that was precisely because you wanted to use force in order to evict the Pakistanis,

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:31.160
[Guest]: but you did not want to use force in ways that would lead to further escalation towards

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:35.480
[Guest]: the sort of nuclear realm. So, in a sense, you are finding that space.

00:37:35.480 --> 00:37:40.840
[Guest]: In fact, after the Kargil war, then Defence Minister George Fernandes gave a speech, where

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:47.280
[Guest]: he sort of pointedly said that the Kargil war has demonstrated that there is space between

00:37:47.280 --> 00:37:52.140
[Guest]: the conventional and the nuclear realm, where India can use force in order to bring things

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:56.960
[Guest]: to bear. But of course, you know, using force on the scale of things of Kargil with the

00:37:56.960 --> 00:38:01.480
[Guest]: degree of restraint was only possible because of the peculiar sort of nature of that conflict,

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:06.440
[Guest]: which was about Pakistanis doing a land grab on the Indian side of the line of control,

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:11.860
[Guest]: right. But the problem of terrorism still proved quite difficult to crack. So, for instance,

00:38:11.860 --> 00:38:16.700
[Guest]: in the period after the nuclear tests and the Kargil conflict, you had a fairly sort

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:21.960
[Guest]: of intense period where India was using various kinds of conventional means to deter Pakistani

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:25.440
[Guest]: support for infiltration of terrorism across the line of control, right. So, you sort of

00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:30.540
[Guest]: hit them very hard with artillery weapons, constant small arms firing, even actions across

00:38:30.540 --> 00:38:36.120
[Guest]: the line of control, right, by what were sort of informally called, you know, BATs. So,

00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:41.000
[Guest]: you know, you would sort of go across, hit them, punish them, and tell them that listen,

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:44.720
[Guest]: supporting infiltration from this sector is not a cost free option for you, right. So,

00:38:44.720 --> 00:38:49.360
[Guest]: that was one way of doing it. But when you had a significant terrorist strike, like what

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:55.280
[Guest]: happened in by way of the attack on Parliament in India in December 2001, then the government

00:38:55.280 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: felt that, you know, you had to respond much more strongly. But once again, you felt that

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:03.040
[Guest]: air power was not possibly the best way of doing it. And then you mobilise the all your

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:09.000
[Guest]: armed forces, threaten Pakistan with a serious strike. But once the Pakistanis counter mobilised,

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:12.840
[Guest]: and once the rest of the international community got into the action, you very quickly realised

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:16.960
[Guest]: that carrying out major conventional operations against Pakistan would be very risky.

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:22.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Musharraf explicitly said that our response to escalation may not be conventional

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:23.840
[Guest]: alone.

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:24.840
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:25.840
[Guest]: Explicitly threatened.

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:29.480
[Guest]: So, for Pakistan, it makes sense for them to sort of try and negate India's conventional

00:39:29.480 --> 00:39:33.760
[Guest]: superiority, right. So, so the search for the space between the conventional and the

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:38.920
[Guest]: nuclear realm, where India could effectively use force to deter terrorism, continues after

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:42.640
[Guest]: the 2001 crisis. That is when you come up with this whole concept of something called

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:47.520
[Guest]: Cold Start, which has never been formally sort of accepted by the Indian government.

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:53.760
[Guest]: But broadly speaking, the idea was that one of the major problems in the 2001-2002 crisis

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:57.800
[Guest]: was that it took about three weeks before your entire armed forces could be mobilised,

00:39:57.800 --> 00:40:01.640
[Guest]: particularly a strike course, which are capable of carrying out, you know, serious offensive

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:04.280
[Guest]: operations and imposing costs on Pakistan.

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:08.640
[Guest]: So, you came up with this idea that it would be good to have, you know, formations which

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:13.400
[Guest]: are capable of hitting across, maybe capturing some territory, imposing costs on the Pakistan

00:40:13.400 --> 00:40:18.840
[Guest]: army, but which did not require this kind of long gestation period of mobilisation and

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:22.800
[Guest]: so on. So, it would be a cold, a standing start or a cold start was the way that you

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:27.320
[Guest]: were thinking. But the Pakistani response to that was to then say that, you know, we

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:33.320
[Guest]: are going to then lower the sort of nuclear threshold by a developing nuclear weapons,

00:40:33.320 --> 00:40:37.680
[Guest]: which can be used in more sort of practical ways, i.e. in an operational battlefield kind

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:43.360
[Guest]: of context, and by devolving some of these sort of weapons further down the chain of

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:48.360
[Guest]: command, right. So, you increase the risks of nuclear escalation for India.

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:52.540
[Guest]: So, if India is going to think about saying that, listen, okay, we are going to send our

00:40:52.540 --> 00:40:56.960
[Guest]: armoured formation or whatever cold start kind of operation across. And when we are

00:40:56.960 --> 00:41:01.840
[Guest]: on their side of the international boundary or line of control, the Pakistanis use a tactical

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:06.640
[Guest]: nuclear weapon, what are you going to do? Because they have used nuclear weapons in

00:41:06.640 --> 00:41:11.040
[Guest]: response to a conventional operation by you on their own territory, right. That then puts

00:41:11.040 --> 00:41:14.720
[Guest]: you in a great dilemma of saying, are you going to respond now really by that massive

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:16.600
[Guest]: retaliation strike that you promised?

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:17.600
[Guest]: Because there's an issue of proportionality.

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:22.760
[Guest]: Proportionality and, you know, whether the issue merits that kind of a response. So,

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:25.720
[Amit Varma]: that search for that space, therefore, continues, right.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:31.400
[Amit Varma]: And the problem, another problem with the cold start also would be that it's hard for

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:36.520
[Amit Varma]: us to predict what action they will consider sufficiently escalatory to go nuclear. So,

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:40.960
[Amit Varma]: we might think, for example, that we will go as far as point X and then we will come

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:46.320
[Amit Varma]: back, but they don't know that. So, you know, for example, you know, if we go into POK,

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:49.560
[Amit Varma]: that's one thing, and it might not even be sufficient provocation. But if we go anywhere

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:53.840
[Amit Varma]: in Punjab or Sindh, you know, Lahore is 25 kilometers from the border. We go 10 kilometers

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:58.400
[Amit Varma]: in, it's an existential threat for them. They could just go nuclear. So, since we don't

00:41:58.400 --> 00:42:03.000
[Amit Varma]: know that, then as a matter of precaution, we don't go anywhere.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:07.860
[Guest]: Well, I mean, so that's the problem, right? Which is that nobody really knows where those

00:42:07.860 --> 00:42:14.720
[Guest]: red lines are. The Pakistani army and, you know, the head of the strategic plans division

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:19.440
[Guest]: back in the day had enunciated some red lines and so on. But there is every incentive for

00:42:19.440 --> 00:42:25.280
[Guest]: Pakistan to keep those as hazy as possible, because you want to introduce uncertainty

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:29.360
[Guest]: in the minds of the Indian decision maker, right? You know, Thomas Schelling used to

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:33.920
[Guest]: say that, you know, there is a threat that leaves something to chance. That is exactly

00:42:33.920 --> 00:42:38.360
[Guest]: the kind of posture that the Pakistanis will want to adopt, which is to say that, listen,

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:43.360
[Guest]: you don't know. And actually, frankly, even we don't know, because we will only know it

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:48.400
[Guest]: when we are in that crisis. And at that point of time, if you are going to use this particular

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:53.560
[Guest]: sort of option, then, you know, we genuinely don't know how we're going to do it. And again,

00:42:53.560 --> 00:42:57.160
[Guest]: you know, Tom Schelling, who wrote some of the most classic pieces of work on thinking

00:42:57.160 --> 00:43:01.520
[Guest]: through some of these dynamics of nuclear strategy, has this fantastic sort of, you

00:43:01.520 --> 00:43:05.760
[Guest]: know, an image or a metaphor, example of how this works.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:11.280
[Guest]: He says, think of two men in a boat, right? Both of whom are trying to say that one wants

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:15.200
[Guest]: the boat to go in the direction of one bank, and the other one wants to push it in the

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:20.880
[Guest]: other, right? So what's the best way of sort of convincing the other person is to start

00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:26.640
[Guest]: rocking the boat. Because when you rock the boat, what you're threatening is not that,

00:43:26.640 --> 00:43:30.280
[Guest]: you know, the other person will incur costs, but you're saying that both of them are going

00:43:30.280 --> 00:43:34.480
[Guest]: to incur costs, and we just don't know what point the boat is going to tip over, right?

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:38.360
[Guest]: So those are threats that leave something to chance. And for Pakistan, it makes absolute

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:43.080
[Guest]: rational sense to adopt that kind of a posture, rather than allowing India to say that, listen,

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:47.800
[Guest]: we can be very sure of what is it that is going to trigger a nuclear use with Pakistan.

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:52.200
[Guest]: Now, Indian decision makers may well believe that, no, Pakistanis are bluffing that actually

00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:56.520
[Guest]: their nuclear threshold is much higher, it is much further interior and so on. But can

00:43:56.520 --> 00:43:58.440
[Guest]: you be sure?

00:43:58.440 --> 00:44:02.040
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, is it like, you know, what game theorists would call the game of chicken

00:44:02.040 --> 00:44:06.800
[Amit Varma]: where the more irrational party has a distinct advantage? And in this case, Pakistan can

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:11.320
[Amit Varma]: portray themselves as irrational, and you don't know what they're up to. But Indians,

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:17.160
[Amit Varma]: unfortunately, stick to a very sort of rational playbook. And that ship has probably sailed,

00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:21.680
[Amit Varma]: we can't really portray ourselves as too irrational right now. But in that game of chicken, we

00:44:21.680 --> 00:44:23.280
[Amit Varma]: are, we are losing, we are behind.

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:28.080
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I think the sort of, you know, the example of chicken might exaggerate the

00:44:28.080 --> 00:44:32.240
[Guest]: elements of irrationality, which say a country like Pakistan has to demonstrate in this case,

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:38.600
[Guest]: Pakistan is a conventionally weaker, geographically smaller. And for them, it's, it's perfectly

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:44.120
[Guest]: rational to say that, listen, as the much smaller and weaker of the two sides, if we

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:51.120
[Guest]: believe we are under threat, then we may use whatever is at hand. We don't know. We just

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:55.280
[Guest]: cannot be sure. It's not about you cannot be sure, even we cannot be sure where those

00:44:55.280 --> 00:44:57.000
[Amit Varma]: red lines are. That's the only way to play this game.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but in the game of chicken, it's always rational to portray yourself as a more irrational

00:45:00.520 --> 00:45:02.280
[Guest]: like Kim does in North Korea, for example.

00:45:02.280 --> 00:45:06.680
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly. So, in this context, I mean, I think the Pakistanis have, you know, you

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:12.360
[Guest]: know, precisely all the incentives to act in ways that suggest that these things will

00:45:12.360 --> 00:45:17.400
[Guest]: go out of control. And again, you know, this is not a hypothetical. If you, we'll come

00:45:17.400 --> 00:45:23.880
[Guest]: to the latest sort of crisis. But if you recall, when Imran Khan, the Prime Minister of Pakistan,

00:45:23.880 --> 00:45:28.700
[Guest]: gave a televised press speech, and this was even before the Indian airstrike happened,

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:35.280
[Guest]: he said, that, listen, you know, if India uses force, it's not like we will think of

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:40.280
[Guest]: using force, we will actually have to retaliate. And thereafter, you know, nobody knows all

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:45.600
[Guest]: bets are off. And that is exactly the rational approach to take for Pakistan by telling India

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:49.760
[Guest]: that listen, it's not just that you can guess or not guess where our red lines are, even

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:50.760
[Amit Varma]: we don't know.

